    structure:
      "What will I study on the course?\nFilm Theory & Visual\nSubtext Intro to genre, structure, and mise-en-sc\u00e8ne\nHow visuals communicate meaning and emotion\nUse of framing, movement, and colour for subtext\nSymbolism, mood, and metaphor in film\nAnalysing iconic scenes for visual storytelling techniques\nApplying theory to students\u2019 own film ideas\nDeveloping Ideas &\nScriptwriting Techniques Brainstorming ideas from experience or prompts\nWhat makes a strong short film idea (unique, emotional, contained)\nBasic structure: setup, conflict, resolution\nVisual storytelling and writing for the screen\nWriting loglines, outlines, and short scripts\nDeveloping Characters Creating compelling, flawed characters with goals\nInternal vs external conflict\nCharacter backstory and motivation\nShowing character through actions and choices\nExercises in dialogue and character development\nCasting & Directing Actors Casting: how to run auditions and select talent\nDirecting actors with clarity and confidence\nRehearsals, blocking, and emotional beats\nBuilding trust and safe spaces on set\nFilming test scenes and giving direction\nPre-Production Finalising script, shot list, and schedule\nVisual planning: storyboards and look references\nLocation scouting, permissions, and equipment prep\nRoles, crew planning, and health & safety\nOrganising production documents\nCamera Techniques &\nSettings Basic camera settings: ISO, aperture, shutter speed\nComposition and framing for story and emotion\nMovement: handheld, tripod, sliders\nManual focus, B-roll, and coverage strategies\nShooting simple scenes and reviewing footage\nCinematic Lighting Natural vs artificial lighting\n3-point lighting and its variations\nUsing light for mood, tone, and style\nColour temperature, gels, shadows, and contrast\nLow-budget lighting tips and practical setups\nRecording Audio Microphone types and best use cases\nCapturing clean dialogue and ambient sound\nBoom mic operation and field recorders\nAvoiding common sound issues\nSyncing audio and preparing for post-production\n5 Days of Filming Students shoot short films in groups\nApplying all learned skills on set\nManaging time, resources, and collaboration\nCapturing coverage and maintaining continuity\nAdapting to real-world challenges\n5 Days of Editing Importing footage and creating timelines\nRough cuts, pacing, and refining edits\nBasic sound design and music\nColour correction and titles\nExporting final cuts and peer feedback\nWorkshop with Elliot Grove & Short Film Screenings Elliot\u2019s insights on indie filmmaking and producing\nIndustry advice and open Q&A\nScreening all student films\nFeedback, celebration, and reflection\nNext steps: festivals, careers, and development",
